```{r}
#| label: intro-setup
#| include: false
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  eval = TRUE,
  fig.width = 7,
  fig.height = 5,
  fig.path = "img/"
)
library(ggseg3d)
library(dplyr)
```

ggseg3d renders interactive 3D brain atlases using WebGL via Three.js.
It provides a pipe-friendly API and unified brain atlases that work with both
ggseg (2D) and ggseg3d (3D).

## Getting started

```{r}
#| label: intro-basic
library(ggseg3d)

ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  pan_camera("left lateral")
```

Call `ggseg3d()` without arguments to plot the default Desikan-Killiany atlas.
The widget is interactive: rotate by clicking and dragging, zoom with the scroll
wheel, and hover over regions to see their names.

## Mapping data

Provide a data frame with a `region` column matching the atlas, and map a
variable to `colour_by`:

```{r}
#| label: intro-plot-data
#| eval: false
library(dplyr)

some_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.01, 0.04, 0.2, 0.5)
)

ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", text_by = "p") |>
  pan_camera("right lateral")
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-snap-plot-data
#| include: false
some_data <- tibble(
  region = c("precentral", "postcentral", "insula", "superior parietal"),
  p = c(0.01, 0.04, 0.2, 0.5)
)

ggseg3d(.data = some_data, atlas = dk(), colour_by = "p", text_by = "p") |>
  pan_camera("right lateral") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/intro-plot-data.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-fig-plot-data
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Brain regions coloured by p-value."
knitr::include_graphics("img/intro-plot-data.png")
```

## Subcortical atlases

For subcortical structures, use the `aseg` atlas and add a translucent glass
brain for anatomical context:

```{r}
#| label: intro-subcortical
#| eval: false

subcort_data <- tibble(
  region = c("Thalamus", "Caudate", "Hippocampus"),
  p = c(0.2, 0.5, 0.8)
)

ggseg3d(.data = subcort_data, atlas = aseg(), colour_by = "p", na_alpha = .5) |>
  add_glassbrain()
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-snap-subcortical
#| include: false
subcort_data <- tibble(
  region = c("Thalamus", "Caudate", "Hippocampus"),
  p = c(0.2, 0.5, 0.8)
)

ggseg3d(
  .data = subcort_data,
  atlas = aseg(),
  colour_by = "p",
  na_alpha = .5
) |>
  add_glassbrain() |>
  snapshot_brain("img/intro-subcortical.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-fig-subcortical
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Subcortical structures with a translucent glass brain overlay."
knitr::include_graphics("img/intro-subcortical.png")
```

## Camera and background

Use `pan_camera()` to set the viewing angle and `set_background()` to change
the background colour:

```{r}
#| label: intro-camera
#| eval: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  set_background("black")
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-snap-camera
#| include: false
ggseg3d(hemisphere = "left") |>
  pan_camera("left lateral") |>
  set_background("black") |>
  snapshot_brain("img/intro-background.png")
```

```{r}
#| label: intro-fig-camera
#| echo: false
#| fig.cap: "Brain atlas with a black background."
knitr::include_graphics("img/intro-background.png")
```

Available presets include `"left lateral"`, `"right medial"`,
`"left superior"`, and more. For custom positions, pass a list with
`eye` coordinates.


